         <title>NOTES</title>
         <ref id="ref1">
            <label>1.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">In “Husserl's Problematic Concept of the Life-World,” David Carr points out that<italic>Crisis</italic>is the product of Husserl's last illness. This explains in part why in that work there is “a serious ambiguity in Husserl's notion of the life-world” (<year>1977</year>,<fpage>210</fpage>). In<italic>Crisis</italic>, Husserl seems to vacillate between a lifeworld that is fundamentally cultural and one that is fundamentally a world of immediate experience.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">The translators choose to render<italic>Stimmung</italic>as “mood,” but according to the<italic>Oxford Duden</italic>and<italic>Langenscheidt, Stimmung</italic>in the sense of public opinion is within the range of idiomatic German. To tune an instrument to its proper pitch is another meaning of<italic>Stimmung</italic>, mentioned at xipolis.net. It is routine for Heidegger to tap into these metaphoric correspondences, all of which are, I think, appropriate in this context.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref3">
            <label>3.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Throughout this paper, I refer to African Americans as Negroes in conformity to the usage of the time.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref4">
            <label>4.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">There is no direct evidence of this, as the files of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference are not open to scholars. But this lack of candor itself makes the indirect evidence for this claim more telling.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
